body:
The generated enum variants is hack to bound the type params to the enum itself.
Thus, the enum patterns are never used and will always generated warnings so
this commit adds `unused` on all the variants.

Closing #106 

Example:

```rust
jsonrpsee_proc_macros::rpc_client_api! {
	RpcApi {
		#[rpc(method = "state_getPairs")]
		fn storage_pairs(prefix: StorageKey, hash: Option<Hash>) -> Vec<(StorageKey, StorageData)>;
		#[rpc(method = "chain_getFinalizedHead")]
		fn finalized_head() -> Hash;
	}
}
```

Expands to:

```rust
enum RpcApi {
    StoragePairs {
        prefix: StorageKey,
        hash: Option<Hash>,
    },
    FinalizedHead {},
    #[allow(unused)]
    _0(Vec<(StorageKey, StorageData)>),
    #[allow(unused)]
    _1(Hash),
}
impl RpcApi {
    async fn storage_pairs(
        client: &impl jsonrpsee_types::traits::Client,
        param0: impl Into<StorageKey>,
        param1: impl Into<Option<Hash>>,
    ) -> core::result::Result<Vec<(StorageKey, StorageData)>, jsonrpsee_types::error::Error>
    where
        Vec<(StorageKey, StorageData)>: jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::DeserializeOwned,
        StorageKey: jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::Serialize,
        Option<Hash>: jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::Serialize,
    {
        client
            .request(
                "state_getPairs",
                jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::Params::Map({
                    let mut map = jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::JsonMap::with_capacity(2usize);
                    map.insert(
                        "prefix".to_string(),
                        jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::to_value(param0.into()).map_err(|e| {
                            jsonrpsee_types::error::Error::Custom({
                                let res = ::alloc::fmt::format(::core::fmt::Arguments::new_v1(
                                    &[""],
                                    &match (&e,) {
                                        (arg0,) => [::core::fmt::ArgumentV1::new(
                                            arg0,
                                            ::core::fmt::Debug::fmt,
                                        )],
                                    },
                                ));
                                res
                            })
                        })?,
                    );
                    map.insert(
                        "hash".to_string(),
                        jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::to_value(param1.into()).map_err(|e| {
                            jsonrpsee_types::error::Error::Custom({
                                let res = ::alloc::fmt::format(::core::fmt::Arguments::new_v1(
                                    &[""],
                                    &match (&e,) {
                                        (arg0,) => [::core::fmt::ArgumentV1::new(
                                            arg0,
                                            ::core::fmt::Debug::fmt,
                                        )],
                                    },
                                ));
                                res
                            })
                        })?,
                    );
                    map
                }),
            )
            .await
    }
    async fn finalized_head(
        client: &impl jsonrpsee_types::traits::Client,
    ) -> core::result::Result<Hash, jsonrpsee_types::error::Error>
    where
        Hash: jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::DeserializeOwned,
    {
        client
            .request(
                "chain_getFinalizedHead",
                jsonrpsee_types::jsonrpc::Params::None,
            )
            .await
    }
}
```

Closes #103

The spec for `batch requests` can be found [here](https://www.jsonrpc.org/specification#batch)

The implementation is a little bit inefficient as the `server` is free to process the request in the batch in any order such that the client has try any order of the request IDs. Thus,  for each response we have to do linear search to deduce whether a response indeed corresponded to a request because `request IDs` are not necessarily monotonically increasing.

Then for the RequestManger/WebSocket I added `batch request` where the requestIDs are "sorted" (inserted as BTreeSet). Then when a batch response is received it's converted to a `BTreeSet` and checked in the `RequestManager` but the order needs to be preserved so still have to do linear search to achieve the same order as the request was performed.

We could maybe move the request ID management to user to avoid return the requests in the same order but for now it's required.

An example of this:

```rust
let reqs = vec![("method": "foo",  "params": []), ("method": "bar", "params": [1, 2, 3])];
let response = client.batch_request(reqs).await.unwrap();
// without order it could return
vec!["foo_response", "bar_response"]
vec!["bar_response", "foo_response"]
// The user has no idea how to associate a response with a request.
```

Further, batch requests does consume a `request ID` for each request in the batch and it "might violate" the "max_concurrent_request_limit" depending on how we define that I suppose. For example if a user sets this to 10 and then perform a batch request of 10, then no more requests are allowed until the batch has been completed. So question is that if a batch request should be regarded as one request or the number of requests in the batch

//cc @insipx as user of this API, does it make sense? Perhaps we should document the expectations explicitly that the request are answered in the same order as submitted to `fn batch_request`. That's the only way the associate a request with a response.

This PR introduces a client trait to support to `jsonrpsee_proc_macros` again and refactor the macros to the new client design.
As a bonus it closes #104

Not addressed in this PR:
- subscriptions in `proc macros`
- the trait could use `serde raw value` with Maciej's design instead of `Into<String>, Into<Params`

### Annoyance with the macros

FYI,
One annoyance that I found is how the enums are generated by the `proc macros` which is that all type params on the methods are bound to specific enum variant, to illustrate this:

```rust
jsonrpsee_proc_macros::rpc_client_api! {
	Health {
		fn say_hello<T, B>(t: T) -> B;
	}
}
```

expands to 

```rust
// this won't compile because the type params are not bound
// needs to be enum Health<T, B> { ... }
enum Health {
    SayHello {
        t: T,
    },
    #[allow(unused)]
    _0: B,
}
```

As you can see the entire enum needs to have that type param to compile so a little annoying. So one have to do this instead:

```rust
jsonrpsee_proc_macros::rpc_client_api! {
	Health<T, B> {
		fn say_hello(t: T) -> B;
	}
}
```

One solution,  could be collect all generic params and diff it with `type generics` on the enum and add the missing params manually.
